      "example_rewrite": "## Anti-Patterns\n\n| Anti-Pattern | Why It Fails | Correct Behavior |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Relationship Theater** | Treating regular partner check-ins as status updates with no agenda; partner feels managed, not valued, and disengages at renewal. | Every touchpoint must deliver something — a data insight, an introduction, a content opportunity — before asking for anything. |\n| **Premature Integration Commitment** | Verbally committing a partner to a tech integration launch date before Product Manager confirms sprint capacity; creates legal exposure and destroys trust when missed. | Gate any timeline commitment with a written Integration Readiness Confirmation from the Product Manager before communicating to the partner. |\n| **Deal-Close Abandonment** | Treating a signed agreement as the finish line; partnerships that lack activation plans within 30 days of signing lose momentum and deliver no value. | Activation plan must be drafted and CSO-approved before the agreement is executed, not after. |\n| **One-Contact Dependency** | Building the entire partner relationship through a single champion at the partner org; when that person leaves, the partnership collapses. | Map and engage at least two stakeholders at every partner organization within 90 days of activation. |\n| **Festival Culture Mismatch** | Pitching Love Burn or regional burn partners with corporate sponsorship language (ROI, impressions, deliverables); immediately signals Story Portal doesn't understand the culture. | Use participation, co-creation, and community contribution framing; quantitative metrics are secondary and should be introduced only after relational trust is established. |"
